"# Chapter 11 — The registry: introspecting the whole vocabulary

Every registered verb lives in one map. That map is a value. You can iterate it, filter it, project fields out of it, and build any tool you want on top of it. This chapter shows the registry as a first-class queryable data structure.

## 11.1 snapshot-registry

The primary verb is `snapshot-registry`. It returns a copy of the current registry as a plain object — verb name → metadata record.

```scheme
(snapshot-registry)
;; => a hash-like structure mapping every verb name to its metadata
```

The return is a snapshot — safe to iterate without worrying about mutation. Every subsequent call returns a fresh snapshot.

## 11.2 Iterating the registry

```scheme
(define all-verbs (map car (snapshot-registry)))
(length all-verbs)
;; => 512 (or however many verbs are registered)

(take all-verbs 10)
;; => (car cdr cons list map filter fold apply eval define)
```

The list of names is the vocabulary of the language. You can enumerate it in any order — sorted, filtered by prefix, grouped by namespace.

## 11.3 Filtering by namespace

```scheme
(define (verbs-in-namespace ns)
  (filter
    (lambda (n) (string-prefix? (string-append ns \"/\") n))
    (map car (snapshot-registry))))

(verbs-in-namespace \"cortex\")
;; => (cortex/read cortex/write cortex/record cortex/query cortex/remember cortex/recall)
```

Every cortex verb, in one call. Same for `card/`, `composer/`, `paint-`, etc.

## 11.4 Filtering by perm

```scheme
(define (verbs-with-perm perm)
  (filter
    (lambda (n)
      (equal? perm (cdr (assoc 'perm (help n)))))
    (map car (snapshot-registry))))

(verbs-with-perm \"financial\")
;; => every financial-tier verb — audit this list carefully
```

Filter by any metadata field. The registry is data; every field is queryable.

