## 11.22 Deep-seed — the registry validation step

At startup, `validateRegistry` in `src/verbRegistry.js` walks every registered verb and checks the perm invariant: any name pattern that looks state-changing (ends in `!`, starts with `card-`, etc.) must have an explicit perm, not an inferred one.

```scheme
(validate-registry)
;; either succeeds silently or lists offenders
```

This is the runtime's cheapest safety net against forgotten perm declarations. If a new verb was registered without thinking about perm, the validation catches it before any cart runs.

For introspection purposes: `(validate-registry)` returns nil on success or a list of offending names on failure. You can wire it into CI.

## 11.23 Deep-seed — enumerating deprecated aliases

Some verbs are aliases for others. The metadata records this via `deprecated` and `aliasFor` fields.

```scheme
(define (deprecated-verbs)
  (filter
    (lambda (n)
      (assoc 'deprecated (help n)))
    (map car (snapshot-registry))))

(deprecated-verbs)
;; => (cortex/remember old-name-1 old-name-2)
```

For each, get the canonical name:

```scheme
(map
  (lambda (n) (list n (cdr (assoc 'aliasFor (help n)))))
  (deprecated-verbs))
;; => ((cortex/remember cortex/write) (old-name-1 new-name-1) ...)
```

Now you have a migration map. Every deprecated verb and what to rename it to. A linter can consume this map and flag every deprecated call in a cart with a suggested rename.

## 11.24 Deep-seed — the reference manual is generated from this

`src/docs-emitter.js` walks the registry and emits a section per verb into `scheme/MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat`. Every field the introspection layer reads is what the reference documents.

If you want to regenerate the reference:

```scheme
(emit-reference-manual \"scheme/MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat\")
;; writes a fresh manual from the current registry
```

The manual and the registry are consistent by construction. If the registry adds a verb, the next manual build has it. If the registry loses a verb, the next manual build drops the section.

Turn the page. Chapter 12 opens apropos and search — how to find a verb when you know what you want but not what to call it.

## 11.25 A closing observation on scale

The registry is small. Around five hundred verbs in a typical Motoi runtime. That is small enough to iterate in a millisecond and small enough to hold in your head with practice.

Compare to a JVM classpath with fifty thousand classes, or a JavaScript ecosystem with a million published packages. Motoi's registry is walkable. That walkability is why introspection over the registry is worth doing.

If Motoi ever grows past a few thousand verbs the introspection story will need to be re-thought. For now, the whole language surface is queryable in a fraction of a second, and that speed is what makes the reflex viable.

## 11.26 Turn the page

Chapter 12 opens apropos, find-by-arity, find-by-contract — search over the registry when you know the shape but not the name. Turn the page.

## 11.27 One more small example

If you want to see every verb whose name contains a substring:

```scheme
(filter (lambda (n) (string-contains n \"sort\"))
        (map car (snapshot-registry)))
;; => (sort sort-by sort! sorted? unsort merge-sort)
```

Simple filter, useful result. This is `apropos` under the hood — Chapter 12 will name it and formalize it. Here the primitive is enough.

Turn the page.

## 11.28 Deep-seed — the registry as training data

Motoi Copilot was trained on the registry. Every field on every record contributed. The model learned:

- Verb names (as tokens the model can generate)
- Doc strings (as natural-language associations)
- Contracts (as signature templates)
- Examples (as generation templates)
- Namespaces (as grouping context)
- Perms (as safety hints)

The registry is not just a runtime lookup. It is a corpus. Every well-written verb metadata record is a training pair for the next model iteration.

This is why Chapter 2 emphasized filling in the fields. Every field-that-was-filled-in becomes training signal. Every field-that-was-not becomes a gap the model has to guess through.

## 11.29 Deep-seed — the by-since query

```scheme
(define (verbs-since version)
  (filter
    (lambda (n)
      (equal? version (cdr (assoc 'since (help n)))))
    (map car (snapshot-registry))))

(verbs-since \"1.4\")
;; => every verb added in the 1.4 release
```

Release notes generator, built from introspection. Publish `(verbs-since \"1.4\")` and you have the addition list for the release.

## 11.30 Deep-seed — the by-source query

```scheme
(define (verbs-from-file path)
  (filter
    (lambda (n)
      (let ((src (source-of n)))
        (and src (string-prefix? path src))))
    (map car (snapshot-registry))))

(verbs-from-file \"lib/composer/\")
;; => every verb registered from lib/composer/
```

Grouping by source file often groups by feature. All the composer widgets are in `lib/composer/`; all the audio verbs in `lib/audio/`. This query gives you the feature-level slice.

Turn the page.

## 11.31 Deep-seed — a quality dashboard

Combine everything from this chapter into a live quality dashboard:

```scheme
(define (registry-dashboard)
  (let ((all (snapshot-registry)))
    (list
      :total (length all)
      :core (length (verbs-with-tier \"core\"))
      :extended (length (verbs-with-tier \"extended\"))
      :experimental (length (verbs-with-tier \"experimental\"))
      :undocumented (length (undocumented-verbs))
      :missing-examples (length (verbs-missing-examples))
      :deprecated (length (deprecated-verbs))
      :namespaces (length (unique (namespaces-in-registry))))))
```

Ten fields, one call. Print at the end of every dev session and you know the language's health.

Turn the page. Chapter 12 opens the search family.

## 11.32 Deep-seed — walking the whole map

For a bird's-eye view, dump the registry to a summary form:

```scheme
(define (registry-summary)
  (for-each
    (lambda (entry)
      (let ((name (car entry))
            (meta (cdr entry)))
        (display (string-append
                   name \" [\" (or (cdr (assoc 'namespace meta)) \"base\") \"] \"
                   (or (cdr (assoc 'doc meta)) \"(no doc)\")))
        (newline)))
    (snapshot-registry)))
```

Call `(registry-summary)` and you get every verb, one per line, with namespace and doc. That is the whole language surface in one scroll. Print to a file and you have your own local reference.

## 11.33 Deep-seed — the tiny language browser

Combine namespace enumeration with per-namespace listings and you have a two-level browser:

```scheme
(define (list-namespaces)
  (unique
    (filter (lambda (x) x)
            (map (lambda (n) (cdr (assoc 'namespace (help n))))
                 (map car (snapshot-registry))))))

(define (browse-namespace ns)
  (for-each
    (lambda (n) (display (describe n)) (newline) (newline))
    (verbs-in-namespace ns)))

(list-namespaces)
;; => (base list string number cortex composer paint ...)

(browse-namespace \"cortex\")
;; prints every cortex verb's description
```

Two verbs, one for the namespace list and one for descending into a specific namespace. Now you have a text-mode language browser built from introspection primitives.

This is what Chapters 10 and 11 have been leading to. Small primitives compose into tools. The tools are lightweight enough to write in a session, portable enough to work in any REPL, useful enough to keep in your notes.

Turn the page. Chapter 12 opens search.

## 11.34 A closing observation

The registry is the whole language surface as data. That statement sounds abstract until you use it.

The first time you sit down and write `(map car (snapshot-registry))` and see every verb Motoi has scroll past on stdout, something clicks. The language stops being a mysterious thing you learn from tutorials and starts being a queryable data structure you can examine at will.

That click is the payoff of the introspection layer. The rest of the chapters have all been about specific queries; this chapter is about the underlying map that makes every query possible.

Learn to reach for `snapshot-registry` when you need the whole picture. It is the ground of every other introspection tool in the book.

## 11.35 One final small helper

For your notes, one last helper:

```scheme
(define (my-favorite-verbs)
  '(map filter fold cons car cdr list define lambda let cortex/query cortex/record display describe help apropos))

(for-each
  (lambda (n)
    (display (string-append n \": \" (or (doc-of n) \"(no doc)\"))) (newline))
  (my-favorite-verbs))
```

Curate the list of the fifteen verbs you use most. Wrap them in a helper. Now `(my-favorite-verbs)` gives you your personal one-liner cheat-sheet whenever you need it.

That is the shape of tools you build on top of introspection. Small, personal, one call away.

Turn the page. Chapter 12 opens search — the family of verbs that turns *I know what I want but I forget the name* into *here is the verb, with a working call template attached and the doc string a keystroke away*.
")
